The moral code (broadly speaking) and the political values and culture of the United States of America have produced the most prosperous, free nation on the face of the planet.  The moral code, political values, and culture of Iraq and the rest of the Middle East have produced brutal tyrants, repression, injustice, and a subset of the population who are driven to fly airplanes into big American buildings.  A relativist might say, &quot;But brutal tyrants who slaughter their own people are just as 'good' as the U.S. - who are we to judge them?&quot;  And I would say, &quot;We are the people who they attacked, and will continue to attack, unless we change their political culture and moral values.  They gave us the right to judge them when they killed 3,000 of us unprovoked.&quot;  That is why we did not replace Saddam in 1991, imo.  The cauldron was bubbling, but it had not yet boiled over.  Saddam was a sideshow to what was brewing, and still is, but now Saddam's stubborn stupidity provides a perfect opportunity to do what needs to be done. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/caledhon.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A> at: 3/10/03 3:20:51 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hayzen>Hayzen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 531<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/10/03 4:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=448.topic&index=300>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Morality is not relative.&quot;</span><hr size=1> Elche,<br>
